## Dynamic value - data fields, calculations
Insert **Dynamic fields**:

Drag the data field from the editing area, *Data *section, into the template.

![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

insert miscellaneous *dynamic values*:

- Drag a *dynamic value *into the template.

![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

- Click on the element icon to open the input field for the XPath expression.

![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

You can now either enter the expression directly in the input field, or you can open the *Rule Editor *and create the expression by dragging the necessary elements into the editing area.

- Save the expression with the *Apply *button or with Enter. If you just close the input field without applying(X), any changes will be discarded.

The **Rule Editor **offers not only the data fields for easy insertion, but all functions and operators that can be used in XPath.

The topmost area shows the expression. This can be tested with the *Run *button and the result is then displayed in the *Result *area. If there are any errors, they are displayed in the *Console *area. The *Reference *area provides information and examples for the respective function.

![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

For *calculations *enter the syntax directly into the input field, drag and drop the function into the input window or use the necessary expressions from the *functions *and *operators *areas.

![](data:image/png;base64,)

**Numbers and date formats **can be set with the attributes in the area *Styles &amp; Properties *&gt; *Dynamic value*.

![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

Keep in mind that only certain combinations make sense and are possible; if the settings are wrong, the document cannot be rendered. E.g. if you select the "Date" format, you **must **specify a date format under *pattern*.

You can also change or add number formats in the *pattern *field, e.g. with a currency specification such as .##0.00 Euro.

The formatting options correspond to the options of the node-typ attribute, the pattern to the format-pattern attribute.

## Variable / Global Variable
XSL variables can be used just like programming variables. To create a variable, a name and the value must be given, e.g. a field reference in a complex XML structure or a calculation that uses XPath. This is most often used within the template. The ***Variable ***element can be found in the palette in the *Dynamic *section.

![](data:image/png;base64,)

A variable can be placed in the editor or in the outline using drag &amp; drop, e.g. to set it dynamically in a repeat. After the insertion, a dialog for entering the necessary data appears. After clicking on *Apply*, the local variable is created.

![](data:image/png;base64,)

***Global variables ***can also be defined, they are available for the entire template. You can call up the global variables by clicking on *Variables *in the toolbar on the left. The variables consist of *Variable name *and *Expression*. By clicking on the respective name or expression, the data can be edited or added with *Add variable name*. External variables can be added by clicking the folder icon in the *Global Variables (External) *section.

If you move the mouse over one of the global variables, a black menu appears on the right- hand side with the quick access options *open Rule Editor *and *delete*.

![](data:image/png;base64,)

A variable can be called up by using a dynamic value (see chapter [Dynamic value - data fields, calculations](/doxee-platform/docs/6-6-business-designer-user-guide-dynamic-content-1#dynamic-value-data-fields-calculations)) with the $ symbol and the name of the variable (e.g. *$sample variable*).

> Note

*The names of the global, local and external variables must be unique. i.e. a local variable should never use the same name as a global or external variable. *

> Note

*In the settings [Symbol] you can choose to hide or show the variable elements. When elements are hidden, you will only see small placeholders, but you can still click and modify them from the editor.*

## Repeat - multiple data from the same data set
If several similar data from the same data set should be used, use the *repeat *element for this purpose.

For example, there could be several article orders for one customer, which would result in the data structure as shown in the following figure:

![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

With the repeat element it is possible to set up a loop for customer/orders/order and thus to read out the values for each occurrence of "order" contained therein - for this example it is position, article number, product description etc.

Procedure:

- Insert repeat element.

![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

![](data:image/png;base64,)

- Enter the parent data field of the data fields to be repeated (in the example above "order") into the XPath expression of the repeating element ("Repeat") by clicking on the repeat icon.

![](data:image/png;base64,)

- Drag the (child) data fields to be repeated **into **the repeating element.

![](data:image/png;base64,)

> Note: 

*Remove record number ([1]) to list all child data fields if needed.*

- Where necessary, insert additional text elements between the data fields.

![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

> Note

*If only the first record of the data set is printed in the PDF, remember to remove the record number from the child data fields.*

From the Version 6.3 sorting in the repeat element is supported. While editing the repeat expression, the user can also configure the sorting parameters.

![](data:image/png;base64,)

## Conditions
To insert content dependent on specific data in the data source, use a condition element. To do this, drag a condition element to the desired position in the template. This creates a condition branch at the same time. Then drag as many additional *condition branches *as necessary onto the inserted condition element. See also [Insert conditional content](/doxee-platform/docs/6-6-business-designer-user-guide-create-and-edit-templates-short-instruction-guide-1#insert-conditional-content).

![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

A condition element is comparable to an if-then-else statement. It can have several options; these options are the condition branches. Condition branches are the actual containers for the content of a condition, i.e. the content to be displayed if the condition in a branch is true. The respective condition itself is inserted as XPath expression. A condition branch without expression is an "Else" branch. The Else branch must be the last expression, because the branches are processed in their order during rendering.

Conditions must always contain at least one branch. The "Else" branch is optional.

![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

Conditions can be contained in blocks or on block level. Depending on where the condition is located, the condition branches can contain inline- or block-level elements.

If you want to insert more extensive content depending on specific data, it can be useful to first insert all the content normally - preferably in separate containers - and then simply drag the containers in the outline into the condition branches.

Depending on the data situation or the logical requirements, it may be more practical or even necessary to create several condition elements with only one branch each, as shown in the following figure. If several conditions should apply (e.g. customer A gets only one text, but customer B gets two texts), then several elements each with one branch are necessary. But even if the conditions could logically be given into one condition element (each customer gets only one text), it might be more practical to create single condition elements first - and then simply drag the branches with all their contents into the first condition element, which automatically becomes condition branch 2, condition branch 3, etc.

![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

## De-/Activate Element
The *De-/Activate *element can be used to simply show / hide optional content. You can find the element in the palette under *Dynamic*.

![](data:image/png;base64,)

The element works like a condition with the expression "true()" to activate or false() to deactivate content. If the element is added into the editor (drag&amp;drop), it will be displayed as follows:

![](data:image/png;base64,)

The element has a slider that changes its status by click. Blue = active with the condition true() or white = inactive with the condition false(). If the status is active, the content can be edited and it is visualized in the final document.

If the status is inactive, the content is not visualized in the final document and cannot be edited in the editor. In this case, the element is grayed out. The content can only be edited when the slider is active.

![](data:image/png;base64,)

The De-/Activate element can also be nested

![](data:image/png;base64,)

If the parent element is deactivated, the content and the slider of all child elements can no longer be edited and the content is not visualized in the final document.

![](data:image/png;base64,)

If the parent element is activated and the child element is deactivated, the content of the child element is not visualized in the final document.

![](data:image/png;base64,)

In combination with *Content-Security*, the element can be activated and editing can be blocked for certain users. In this example, the content is visualized in the final document. The blocked users will see the element grayed out (editable-template=deny:user:xyz) and they cannot change the slider or the content.

![](data:image/png;base64,)

Content security can also be applied in nested elements. If the editable-template setting of a parent element is set, the setting will be inherited and all child elements have the same status. However, the setting can be overwritten locally e.g. with grant:user:xyz (with available rights) and this can be used to control whether, for example, the parent element is blocked for editing, but the child element is editable. The following is an example with locally overwritten content security:

![](data:image/png;base64,)

Parent element has the condition set to true() and editable-template=**deny**:user:xyz Child element has the condition set to true() and editable-template=**grant**:user:xyz

## Wrap with function
As of Business Designer Version 6.1, the *wrap with *function is available. Elements can thus be wrapped with a *condition *or *repeat*. The function is available in the context menu by right- clicking on the respective element in the editor or in the outline. The function is also available in tables. Table rows and columns can be wrapped with a condition or a repeat.

![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

## Link-Element  web links, references
If you want to insert hyperlinks to website addresses or similar, use the Link element, select the type **external**.

The link element is also used to create links within the template - in this case select the type

### internal.
To create a link, drag the link element to the desired position and then enter the content to be displayed as a link and the link destination - under *URL *for external links or under *ID *for internal links.

![](data:image/png;base64,)

![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

- Content

- Target

Link elements work similarly to HTML links, i.e. like content enclosed in a link. As in HTML, a link is separated from its content. If a link element has no content, the link cannot be displayed in the PDF view.

Enter content: For a text link, simply type the text in the link. To link an image, drag the image element into the link. Link elements can contain any type of inline element (text, image, data field, condition, etc.).

External links:

For the use as a hyperlink, the text of the link element must still be formatted as desired, so there is no automatic, perhaps unwanted formatting of the text.

> Note

http://)

Internal links:

To set a link within the template you first have to assign an ID to the target element. To do so, enter a name or number for the target element under *Styles &amp; Properties *&lt; *Advanced *&lt; *Miscellaneous *&lt; for the id attribute. This number or name must be unique in this template.

You then enter this ID as the destination address of the internal link (the ID is stored in the internal-destination attribute).

*Further link properties can be found under Styles &amp; Properties *&lt; *Advanced *&lt; *Dynamic Effects*. Internal links are also used to create a table of contents if it is required.

## Barcode Element
Barcode Element is a generator of different Barcode types, where the content of the barcode usually comes from data input.

Having a Barcode element selected it is possible to manipulate its properties using the Barcode tab of the Properties view. A barcode always needs to have an XPath expression and a type, otherwise the template cannot be rendered. From currently 38 different types of barcodes (e.g. QR-code, datamatrix, EAN), the desired one has to be selected. Also there are two different barcode generators available (Barcode4j and Aspose) which can be selected in Advanced &gt; Barcode &gt; barcode-generator.

With Version 6.4. the Swiss Barcode type is introduced with additional properties required for this specific type of barcode.

## Check dynamic elements
To check for valid syntax, an option is provided for dynamic elements which can be activated with the *Validate *button.

![](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

This checks if the expression contains valid code and if it can be resolved, i.e. if the statement is feasible.

It is also possible to validate expressions in the Rule Editor where hints are displayed that can

help with the correction, as well as examples for the correct use of functions.

## Processing Instruction
Some renderers allow you to pass renderer specific information or data via Processing Instructions Element. The element is placed in the Dynamic Elements Palette section.

![](data:image/png;base64,)

There are two parameters to fill when dropping the element inside the document: *target*, name of the processing instruction and *data*, the instruction. For detailed overview how to create an instruction, please refer to [https://www.w3.org/TR/2021/REC-xslt20-20210330/#](https://www.w3.org/TR/2021/REC-xslt20-20210330/#creating-processing-instructions) [creating-processing-instructions](https://www.w3.org/TR/2021/REC-xslt20-20210330/#creating-processing-instructions) Website.

> Note

*Do not place the processing instruction element inside or between the test cases, since it is known it can cause problems.*

> Note

*In the settings [Symbol] you can choose to hide or show the processing instruction elements. When elements are hidden, you will only see small placeholders, but you can still click and modify them from the editor.*

## Composer Element
This element is used to control specific functionality in Composer, which is not (yet) supported in Business Designer.

![](data:image/png;base64,)

There are several types of Elements that are configured through the Composer elements:

### Composer Signature
The Composer signature element allows you to insert a signing area in the document. The signature area is marked as X in composer and defines the area to scribble your signature in a browser window using a mouse or a stylus pen. To achieve this, set the composer-element- type via Advanced &gt; Composer &gt; **composer-element-type **as *signature*. The rectangular dimensions (layout) of the signature area also have to be configured in JSON syntax via Advanced &gt; Composer &gt; composer-element-content. For more information about JSON syntax, please refer to [https://www.json.org/json-en.html](https://www.json.org/json-en.html).

### Composer Take-picture
This element offers you the capability to take live photos to be added to the document. The configuration is quite similar to the composer signature element except that you have to change the **composer-element-type **to *take-picture*.

### Composer gps-location
The Composer gps-location element allows you to insert into your document the current geographical position based on the GPS coordinates (latitude, longitude, altitude) of your device or a calculation of the web browser. The composer element type is configured via Advanced &gt; Composer &gt; composer-element-type as *gps-location-button*. You need as well to specify the attribute composer-data with any of these supported values: latitute, longitude, altitude or accuracy. For more details, please refer to composer documentation.

### Composer Barcode Scanner
The Composer barcode element allows you to scan and recognize various barcode symbologies from your document. The recognizer reads the barcodes via built-in camera on your device. The barcode picture is captured and the decoded barcode information is saved on your document. The attribute Advanced &gt; Composer &gt; composer-element-type gets the value *barcode*.

> Note

*Currently the comparison feature does not recognize the Composer Element. This is an improvement that will be done in the future.*

## Free Texts
With the help of Free Texts the FO code can be enriched with individual statements. Right click first on the desired element and select Edit Free Texts in the context menu. In the Pop- up dialog we can create nodes and attributes around the element that will be created:

![](data:image/png;base64,)

> Note

*Currently the comparison fails if the freetext is set inside the template. This is a known bug that will be solved in the future.*

*If freetext syntax is incorrect, it can cause a corrupted document structure while trying to render a PDF.*
